        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a cheerful and energetic 7-year-old girl with bright brown eyes and shoulder-length curly hair, currently appearing visibly uncomfortable and fatigued during her clinic visit. Her cheeks are flushed, and she intermittently winces when swallowing, clutching her throat with her small hand. She is dressed in a colorful unicorn-patterned shirt and is accompanied by her worried mother, who reports the symptoms began two days ago. Notably, {patientName} has also been complaining of intermittent stomach ache since yesterday, which her mother attributes to the difficulty eating and swallowing.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is an active and social child who attends second grade at her local elementary school, where she shares a classroom with 22 other students. Several children in her class have been absent recently due to throat infections, and she spends considerable time in close contact with classmates during group activities, shared meals in the cafeteria, and playground play — all settings well known to facilitate droplet and contact transmission of respiratory pathogens. She loves drawing, playing with her two indoor cats, and riding her bicycle in the neighborhood park on weekends. She participates in an after-school art club twice a week. Her diet is generally balanced, though she has a well-known sweet tooth and frequently consumes sugary snacks and occasional carbonated beverages, which may contribute to minor mucosal irritation of the oropharynx.\n\nHer mother reports that {patientName} started complaining of a sore throat two days ago, followed by difficulty swallowing and a low-grade fever peaking at 38.4°C. She has been eating less than usual, preferring soft foods and cold drinks to soothe her throat. She has had one episode of mild headache and appears more tired than normal. There is no reported cough, runny nose, or ear pain. Her brother (age 10) had a similar sore throat episode about a week prior that resolved on its own, and several classmates have recently been absent with throat infections.\n\n{patientName} lives with her parents and her older brother in a suburban home. She is currently taking loratadine daily for allergic rhinitis — a condition that causes chronic nasal congestion and postnasal drip, which is a known predisposing factor for pharyngeal irritation and recurrent pharyngitis. The household includes two indoor cats. There is no tobacco smoke exposure in the home.\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} is alert but mildly irritable. Her oropharynx is erythematous with mildly enlarged, reddened tonsils and no visible exudate. Cervical lymph nodes are mildly tender and palpable bilaterally. Ear and nasal passages appear normal. Abdomen is soft with mild diffuse tenderness on palpation, consistent with referred discomfort. Lungs are clear to auscultation."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7ec1a8bb-dea2-48fb-81db-faf1ed6282c4",
      "resource": {
