          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of allergic rhinitis (J30.1), for which she takes loratadine 5 mg once daily. This condition causes chronic nasal congestion and postnasal drip, both of which are established predisposing factors for pharyngeal irritation and recurrent pharyngitis episodes. She was born at full term via uncomplicated vaginal delivery and met all developmental milestones appropriately.\n\n{patientName} has had two prior episodes of acute pharyngitis in the past three years — one at age 5 and one at age 6 — both presenting with sore throat and low-grade fever, managed conservatively with analgesics and increased fluid intake without the need for antibiotics or hospitalization. She has had no prior history of tonsillitis requiring antibiotics or surgical intervention.\n\n{patientName} is up to date on all recommended childhood vaccinations per the national immunization schedule, including influenza vaccine administered in the preceding autumn. She has no known history of asthma, eczema, or recurrent ear infections, and no known immunodeficiency.\n\nShe takes loratadine daily for allergic rhinitis. Her diet includes adequate fruit and vegetable intake but also a notable preference for sweets and carbonated beverages, which may contribute to mild mucosal irritation. She sleeps approximately 9–10 hours per night and is generally in good health. There is no history of tobacco smoke exposure in the household. Family pets include two indoor cats, which are current on their vaccinations."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
